.SS DEFAULT BEHAVIOR
.IP \[bu] 2
If no \f[B]\-\-server\f[R] flags are specified, no servers are started.
.IP \[bu] 2
If endpoint flags (metrics, healthz, pprof, pyroscope) are specified
without http\-address, an HTTP server is automatically created on
127.0.0.1:3366 (loopback only).
.IP \[bu] 2
If \f[B]grpc\-address=tcp\f[R] is specified without a port, defaults to
127.0.0.1:4466 (loopback only).
.IP \[bu] 2
If \f[B]grpc\-address=tcp:<port>\f[R] is specified with a bare port,
binds to 127.0.0.1:<port>.
.IP \[bu] 2
If \f[B]grpc\-address=unix\f[R] is specified without a path, defaults to
/var/run/tracee.sock.
.IP \[bu] 2
Existing Unix socket files are automatically cleaned up before starting
the gRPC server.
.SS SECURITY
Both the HTTP and gRPC TCP servers default to binding on
\f[B]127.0.0.1\f[R] (loopback only).
Earlier versions bound the gRPC TCP server to \f[B]0.0.0.0\f[R] (all
interfaces), which exposed privileged RPCs to the network without
authentication.
The gRPC server has no TLS or authentication; binding to a non\-loopback
address requires network\-level access controls.
.PP
If you previously relied on the implicit wildcard bind for remote gRPC
access, you must now set an explicit bind address:
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[B]gRPC on all interfaces (restore old behavior \[en] use with
caution):\f[R]
.RS 2
.IP
.EX
\-\-server grpc\-address=tcp:0.0.0.0:4466
.EE
.RE
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[B]gRPC on specific network interface (preferred when possible):\f[R]
.RS 2
.IP
.EX
\-\-server grpc\-address=tcp:10.0.0.5:4466
.EE
.RE
.PP
If you previously relied on the implicit wildcard bind for remote HTTP
access (Prometheus scraping, health checks, pprof), you must now set an
explicit bind address:
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[B]HTTP on all interfaces:\f[R]
.RS 2
.IP
.EX
\-\-server http\-address=0.0.0.0:3366 \-\-server metrics
.EE
.RE
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[B]HTTP on specific network interface (preferred when possible):\f[R]
.RS 2
.IP
.EX
\-\-server http\-address=10.0.0.5:3366 \-\-server metrics
.EE
.RE
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[B]Config file equivalent:\f[R]
.RS 2
.IP
.EX
server\f[B]:\f[R]
  http\-address\f[B]:\f[R] \[dq]0.0.0.0:3366\[dq]
  grpc\-address\f[B]:\f[R] \[dq]tcp:0.0.0.0:4466\[dq]
  metrics\f[B]:\f[R] true
  healthz\f[B]:\f[R] true
.EE
.RE
.PP
\f[B]pprof restriction:\f[R] The /debug/pprof/ endpoints are always
restricted to loopback clients regardless of the bind address.
pprof heap dumps can expose sensitive process memory of a privileged
eBPF daemon.
If you need remote pprof access, use an SSH tunnel or port forward.
.PP
\f[B]Kubernetes deployments:\f[R] The Helm chart sets
\f[CR]0.0.0.0:3366\f[R] explicitly and ships a NetworkPolicy that
restricts ingress to Prometheus pods.
If using TCP gRPC in Kubernetes, set an explicit bind address and ensure
NetworkPolicy covers the gRPC port as well.
